<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 84 companion (the human side of quality — code review, coding standards, documentation).
    The chapter is process-, config-, and documentation-centric, so the displayed snippets are tag
    regions inside the artifacts that DO the work, not narration of them: a PR template section
    (.github/pull_request_template.md), a CODEOWNERS rule, a review-checklist item (docs/), the exemplar
    Javadoc-as-contract on a public method, and the Checkstyle rule that enforces Javadoc PRESENCE on the
    public API. The printed artifact and the running/checked artifact are one file.

    A small storefront slice (org.acme.review) carries the documentation standard the chapter argues for:
    one well-documented public class whose Javadoc states the contract (params, return, @throws,
    pre/postconditions, nullability), an explicit failure path (a defined empty result plus fail-fast
    construction guards), and an observability surface (a review-throughput health signal). The module is
    green BECAUSE the public API is documented to the standard the `quality` profile's Checkstyle Javadoc
    rules require — and the chapter's honest edge is made executable: those rules confirm a Javadoc is
    PRESENT and well-formed, never that it says anything true (a present-but-useless Javadoc would pass).

    Runtime dependencies are JDK-only. The one extra GAV is the SpotBugs annotations artifact, on the
    compile path only (provided scope), exactly as the Chapter 27 and 39 modules do.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>code-review-standards-documentation</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 84 — The Part the Machine Can't Do (code-review-standards-documentation)</name>

  <dependencies>
    <!--
      SpotBugs annotations (SOURCE-PIN.md: SpotBugs 4.10.2 line; this module builds against the locally
      cached 4.9.3 engine the companion code is pinned to, so the annotations track that engine). The
      annotation is CLASS-retained (SpotBugs reads bytecode), so `provided` scope keeps it on the compile
      path only and the module's runtime stays JDK-only like the rest of the companion code.
    -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
      <artifactId>spotbugs-annotations</artifactId>
      <version>4.9.3</version>
      <scope>provided</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <!--
    The static-analysis gate this chapter operates is documentation enforcement: Checkstyle's Javadoc
    rules, opt-in via `-Pquality` so the default build stays fast. The chapter's point — "automation
    enforces PRESENCE, not quality" — is the literal job of these rules (MissingJavadocType /
    MissingJavadocMethod / JavadocMethod / SummaryJavadoc), so the printed Javadoc rule and the rule that
    actually checks this module are one artifact.

    The maven-checkstyle-plugin (3.6.0) ships an OLD bundled engine (Checkstyle 9.3); the pinned house
    engine (com.puppycrawl.tools:checkstyle:10.26.1) is pulled in as a plugin-level dependency (the
    "two-pin" lesson — the build plugin and the analyzer engine are versioned separately). This module is
    a direct child of the companion-code root, which pins no quality profile of its own, so the profile is
    declared here (the same shape the Chapter 27 and 39 modules use) and reads the config under this
    module's own config/ dir.

    includeTestSourceDirectory is left at its default (false): the Javadoc-presence rules govern the
    public API, not test classes, so test sources are not Javadoc-checked.
  -->
  <profiles>
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <!--
                failOnViolation defaults to true; stated here because it is exactly the policy the chapter
                discusses (the documentation gate that goes red when a public API ships without its
                contract documented).
              -->
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <!--
            SpotBugs: the bytecode vantage point, wired the same minimal way as the Chapter 27 module so
            the exemplar slice is held to a correctness gate as well as a documentation one. The chapter's
            standing point — a documented, well-formed Javadoc is necessary, never sufficient for a correct
            program — is shown by holding the same green module to both gates.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Low</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
